SIMPLE: passionate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Passionate
<hw>Pas"sion*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>passionatus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>passionn⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable or susceptible of passion, or of different
passions; easily moved, excited or agitated; specifically, easily moved
to anger; irascible; quick-tempered; <as>as, a <ex>passionate</ex>
nature</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Homer's Achilles is haughty and <qex>passionate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized by passion; expressing passion; ardent
in feeling or desire; vehement; warm; <as>as, a <ex>passionate</ex>
friendship</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>passionate</xex> Pilgrim.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Suffering; sorrowful.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Passionate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Passionate
<hw>Pas"sion*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
affect with passion; to impassion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Great pleasure, mixed with pitiful regard,⟦br⟧
The godly king and queen did <qex>passionate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To express feelingly or sorrowfully.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Passionately</ent>⟦br⟧
